ce:section.ce:para:
DSC is the third generation solar cell, with a record efficiency of up to 14.3% on a laboratory scale (Kakiage et al., 2015). The device achieved relatively high conversion efficiencies using inexpensive materials and cost-effective manufacturing process. To compete with first- and second-generations solar cells in the power market, however, lowering the production cost is required for DSCs. The counter electrode (CE) is one of the main components in DSC, operating as a catalyst for the reduction of triiodide to iodide ions (3I−/I−
                     3). The efficiency of DSC is linked to the electrocatalytic activity and electrical conductivity of the CE. The low charge transfer resistance (Rct
                     ) is required for the efficient reduction of the redox couple on the CE surface (Boschloo and Hagfeldt, 2009). In this regard, Pt completely satisfies the above-mentioned requirements and is currently used as CE in the state-of-the-art device. However, the large-scale applications of DSC such as building-integrated photovoltaics require the replacement of expensive noble metals with low-cost and earth-abundant alternative materials while maintaining state-of-the-art catalytic activity. The other aspect that required for practical applications is the stability of CEs. Thus, the development of low Pt-loading or Pt-free stable catalysts for CE materials becomes urgent. The Pt-based nanoalloy catalysts (Omelianovych et al., 2016) and the Pt-based alloy/reduced graphene oxide (RGO) nanohybrid materials were developed and employed as alternative materials for CEs. The lowering of the Pt along with proper experimental analysis of the surface chemistry of nanoalloy is considered as an effective strategy for processing the chemical structure desired for CE (Omelianovych et al., 2018). The related studies have focused on the synthesis of Pt-metal alloys/RGO nanohybrids (where the metals were screened, such as Au, Ni, Co, Pd, Fe, Mo, Cu, Cr, Sn, and Ru) and lowering the Pt utilization while maintaining the high catalytic activity of nanohybrids (Dao et al., 2017; Li et al., 2016, Dao et al., 2018; Wang et al., 2010). The strategy based on tailoring the electronic structures of alloy nanohybrid for minimizing Pt loading and enhancing the catalytic activity of nanohybrid was suggested (Dao et al., 2017). The optimization of PtCo/RGO nanohybrid for the highest catalytic reactivity based on the densityfunctional theory (Hammer and Nørskov, 2000) resulted in an efficiency of 7.44% using the CE with a low Pt loading (Pt0.1Co0.9/RGO). However, the investigations mentioned above have focused on the Pt-based alloy nanocomposites and an expensive noble metal was still used for CEs.

In order to evaluate the catalytic activity of the CoxSn1-x/RGO CEs, we conducted CV measurements for every CE. The corresponding CV curves are shown in Fig. 3
                        a. A typical set of redox peaks was detected. We found that the absolute value of the reduction current obtained from the CE consisting of the Co0.9Sn0.1/RGO was the highest among those recorded for the CEs under study. The result indicates that the Co0.9Sn0.1/RGO sample has the lowest charge transfer resistance (Rct
                        ) among the tested CEs (Xiao and Han, 2015). A larger surface area or higher surface reactivity may be key factors for the reduced charge-transfer resistance.
